On the shelves, items from simple glasscontainers to elaborate designs in color and wrought iron lay neatlyarranged.  A wave of heat and the low roar of the furnaces in the back ofthe shop hits you as apprentices scurry about to aid the masterglassblowers.  Near the oldest of the glassblowers, a woman is carefullycreating a stained glass image using `ncolorful`l shards of glass.  ``

Rooms.EnterMsg: `dThe skins rustle as `h$n `dbrushes past them on the way in.``
Rooms.ExitMsg: `dMore vile fumes are wafted past you as `h$n `dleaves.``
Rooms.RoomDescription: The foul smells of the leather curing process fill this shop, waftingfrom the back room, and mingling with the strong leather scent of theproducts.  Upon the shelves and hanging on hooks on the walls, a greatvariety of well crafted leather goods are available, from the smooth, tinyleather booties of a baby to the rough leather implements necessary for farmwork.  Upon one wall, an exquisite painting hangs, loving brushstrokesdetailing a misty forest, with a half-glimpsed woman.

Rooms.EnterMsg: `g$n weaves in, trying to avoid the clutter.``
Rooms.ExitMsg: `g$n stumbles out, nearly tripping over a small tray near the door.``
Rooms.RoomDescription: You step into a picture of disorder, ancient objects of every design(some which defy any description) lay scattered about haphazardly.  A fewpaintings, clearly of more recent make, hang on the walls; one of a murkydark forest, a goat legged man barely visible amongst the trees, another ofa beautiful young brunette, painted in strong, passionate strokes by aloving hand.  The rest of the shop is littered with relics of the past,available at reasonable prices.

Rooms.EnterMsg: Dust swirls as $n walks in.
Rooms.ExitMsg: Before the dust can settle, $n leaves.
Rooms.RoomDescription: This narrow shop is packed floor to ceiling with books, every wall hasbeen converted into shelving from top to bottom, more books lay in stacks onthe floor.  You cough slightly at the dust in the air, and are overwhelmedby the accumulated knowledge.

This regal hall is painted pure white, trimmed in unfinished wood, givingthe high-roofed chamber a bright, if austere, feel.  Polished silvershields, emblazened with the coats of arms of the noble families of Thesden,hang high up on the walls, mounted on wooden frames.  Open archways lead offthe north, east and south.

Once a grand abode, it was recently converted into a comfortable inn fordiscriminating visitors.  If the sophistication of the inn's guests can bediscerned through the furnishings which decorate this room, it is evidentthat the Whetstone Inn has seen many accomplished travellers.

You aren't clear on how this tavern got its name, but it appears to bequite popular.  The room is crowded with farmers taking a break from sellingin the square and locals.  A wide mural behind the bar depicts a smallfarmhouse surrounded by fields of golden wheat.

Rooms.EnterMsg: $n's jaw drops open as $e sees the weapons on display here.
Rooms.ExitMsg: $n leaves the shop for the busy square outside.
Rooms.RoomDescription: Gleaming swords, axes, maces and spears rest in racks along the walls ofthis shop.  Above the counter, a soot black ship's anchor hangs quite out ofplace, there to remind anyone who may have forgotten about Mincer Ray'spast.

Rooms.EnterMsg: $n strolls in the shop, glancing around.
Rooms.ExitMsg: $n walks out of the shop.
Rooms.RoomDescription: The design of this store is quite spartan, a simple counter with a fewsamples of the master's work hanging behind.  A price list carved into aboard leans in front of the counter.

The conservatory hall echoes with the dissonant sounds of studentsstruggling to draw the right sound out of their instruments.  Aside from thesmall practice rooms nestled in the alcoves, the wide hall is empty andopen, the hard wood floors reverberating notes with your footsteps.  A shortcorridor leads off to the west.

Rooms.EnterMsg: Windchimes above the door sing a melody as $n walks in.
Rooms.ExitMsg: Windchimes above the door jingle acknowledgement of $n's departure.
Rooms.RoomDescription: The shelves of this shop are filled with delicate, glazed ceramics aswell as thick, sturdy pottery.  A sign on the wall reminds you that all ismade from imported Perthshire clay for the highest quality.  A price list istacked up next to the sign.

Rooms.EnterMsg: $n walks into the cool, well lit room.
Rooms.ExitMsg: $n walks out of the bank onto the busy streets outside.
Rooms.RoomDescription: This large stone building has marble tiled floors and a number of darkwooden desks.  A long line of people seem to be waiting for a turn to make adeposit or withdrawal from the bank.

You stand between the ornate iron gates of Ashton Gardens, where the idlerich come to stroll along the meticulously manicured paths.  Far too grandfor a mere park, the gardens were erected as a living monument to thedeceased Lord Ashton, a great patron of diplomacy and natural beauty.  Anenormous, ancient oak tree stands erect in the center of the park to thewest, its gnarled roots providing home to many creatures and birds.  Lovelywalkways lead through the park to the north and south.

Rooms.EnterMsg: $n steps onto the docks, causing them to sway gently.
Rooms.RoomDescription: The time-worn wood of the docks creaks and sways slightly with eachfootstep.  The masts of ships stand out among a forest of ropes to the eastand west.  A few ships with sails raised pull out heading to the open ocean,slowly shrinking to white dots on the horizon.

Smooth, grey flagstones act as a path through the neatly trimmedcourtyard grass to the northern exit of the courtyard.  In the otherdirections, the stalwart walls of Thesden stand.  Before the southern wall,a weathered statue of a cleric trying to exorcise a demon from a bard, hasbeen erected.  The base of the statue has been inscribed with the words"Through preperation and dilligence shall we be strong."

Rooms.EnterMsg: Musty smoke swirls up around $n as $e enters this cozy shop.
Rooms.ExitMsg: A cool breeze whisks into the room as $n leaves through the door.
Rooms.RoomDescription: Dim oil lamps cast a friendly glow over this cluttered litle shop.  Thewall is decorated in oil paintings, mostly of ships sailing in strong windsor rough seas.  The owner, a friendly odd little man, is always good for asmoke, a drink, or a tale of the 'old days'.

You are walking along a perfectly groomed path in the gardens, crunchingtiny white pebbles under your feet.  The fragrance and pollen of exoticflora imported from distant lands fill the air.  Sheared fragile grassalongside the walkway discourage you from traipsing through the gardens.The path leads west into the gardens, and south back to the entrance.

The Thesdian nobles are unashamed of their corpulent wealth and theirindulgent comforts, and it shows in the vanity of these gardens.  Whereother areas of the city might not see light, the sun shines down rapturouslyupon these blessed trees, breathing life into cherry blossoms piled on topof wiry branches.  The gravel path under you shines like a million silverjewels that in a distant dream you remember lead you to some tranquil haven.

The path that circles the Great Oak are pebbles that line the perfectlyupright grasses of the gardens.  As you walk by, they appear to stand morerigid, as if to come to attention.  A bounty of nuts and cones lay strewnupon the ground, a glorious feeding ground for the chipmunks and squirrelsthat make their home in the tree's thick knotted branches.  Theexpansiveness of the oak tree provides shade and shelter for the people whocome to enjoy the peacefulness of the park.

Untempered by the heavy clodding of wagons and packhorses, and the hectictravel of harried traders, Ashton Gardens has been preserved as a naturalsanctuary.  Imported from across the sea, several perinthen trees stand hereregally bearing their bold lavender and teal blossoms.  The cooing of purewhite doves comes from the nearby grass, where they stroll aboutcontentedly, welcoming you into their abode.

You are strolling through Ashton Gardens, the rush of the city so fardistant.  Thin and fat trees alike grow along the northern iron fence, eachunique and pampered.  Nearby, ducks and swans swim contentedly in a smallpond.  The path winds its way around the Great Oak tree, under a peacefulcanopy of branches.

Though you try not to disturb the denizens of this park, the gravellypath crackles unforgivingly under your feet, causing a robin to raise herhead in alarm.  The soft velvety petals of magenta violets adorn theshrubbery to the northwestern border of the park, shielding the heavy ironfence from view.  Carefully tended by Thesdian gardeners specially trainedin the art of flora, Ashton Gardens flourishes in an otherwise grim city.The iron fisted Lords of Thesden permit themselves this only spot of beauty.

The greenery all around you is swathed in a golden light, making thesilken leaves of eucalyptus trees unfurl dazzlingly from the rest of theshrubbery.  The trees lining the western border of the gardens are ladenwith sun ripened fruits.  These fruits, of course, have never seen thewooden crates of Thesden's open air market.  They are plucked by carefulhands and placed in golden baskets on the dining tables of the mostdiscriminating nobles.  The Great Oak rises to the east, the centerpiece ofthe gardens.

Thick ropes, fishing nets and iron-bindings on the door give this wholetavern the feel of a ship's cabin.  Sailors and darkworkers crowd the room,taking a break from their tiring work.  Your feet stick to the floor as youwind your way across the crowded room to the bar.  Along the walls, you seemany `klegendary fish`l mounted for all to see.

The floor of this tavern is sticky from spilled ale and blood.  Thepatrons eye each other warily from their chairs, each carefully placed sotheir backs are towards the wall.  A sign above a small door to the southreads '`iEmployees Only`l'.  The light is dim in the rest of the room, and youcan barely make out the strangers faces and dark walls lost in the shadows.

This room is stunningly well furnished when compared with the squalidconditions outside on the street.  The thieves clearly do well forthemselves.  The walls are finely painted a deep burgandy, and the floorsare polished to shine, hardly what you'd expect.  A heavy curtain hangs overan open doorway to the south.  A small sign above a panel on the westernwall reads '`bExit here`l'.

The staircase opens onto a landing at the end of a short hallway.  Plainwooden doors line the hallway, most with signs hanging on them.  The Mayor'soffice can be found just to the east, and the Zoning office to the west.The hall ends not far off to the south.

Rooms.EnterMsg: $n wanders in the donation room, examining the discarded goods.
Rooms.ExitMsg: Having examined all the wares, $n leaves the donation room content.
Rooms.RoomDescription: `lThis small room is dominated by a large box which stands in the center, a`lsign above it reads`k Donations for the Poor and Needy, Please Help.`lAside from the box the room has no furnishings, just an open doorway leading`l`lback to the main hall to the west.``

In some lands, when a thief has been caught stealing, the offender'shands are cut off.  When a thief fails an assassination attempt, more oftenthan not, the thief has to begin to worry about his or her life.  Thissmall, dark chamber has been created and added to by generations of thievesas a place where those who wish to practice the art of thievery may do so ina relatively safe and quiet place.  As a testament to this, several wrinkledparchments have been hung upon the walls illustrating the best places inwhich members of different races may be backstabbed in the most effectivefashion.  A wooden target upon one of the walls is covered with countlessscoring marks from thrown blades and darts.  Various daggers of differentsizes and shapes as well as other unrecognizable, yet dangerous lookinginstruments, lay scattered across some crates and crude tables in theshadows.

This small, circular, stone chamber is where those that are musically talented learnto stun, disable, maim and even kill opponents with various forms of music and otherskills.  Various illustrated parchments of varying sizes and colors hang upon the wallsto teach the steps in which a bard may defend themselves in certain situations.  Inthe center of the room upon a wooden pole, a dummy of straw has been hung on whichcombative songs and skills can be practiced.

This beautiful office is decorated in hard woods and the most expensivefurnishings available.  The mayor works here, taking care of the day to daybusiness of the city.  Of course, the mayor is really just the king when hewants to be called by a different title, so his efficiency as a mayor isquestionable.  A wide window allows a view of all of Devon Square to thenorth.

`lA barely decipherable `omap`l hangs across the entire back wall of thisoffice, cryptic colored marks spread all over its surface.  No one builds inThesden without the Zoning office's permission, or at least, if they dotheir houses don't last very long.``

Rooms.EnterMsg: Crushing the hay beneath $s feet, $n walks into the stable.
Rooms.ExitMsg: $n walks out of the stable, taking a breath of fresh air.
Rooms.RoomDescription: A vaulted wooden ceiling tops this large building, mostly open spacedivided into stalls for horses.  The floor is covered in hay, mercifullymasking the smells from the horses stalls.  A large area in the back isdedicated to storage of personal mounts.  In a room off to the west you cansee some saddles and bags for sale.

A small landing interrupts a set of stairs that lead up and down.  Thesomber walls are undecorated, still plain black and without markings.  Athick, steel door stands to the west and a narrow archway leads off to thenorth.  Next to the steel door, a note reads `b'CAUTION: Apprentices May`bOnly Use This Room When Supervised'.``

A large chalkboard hangs on the far wall of this small room, marked withobscure runes and symbols.  Only one uncomfortable chair sits across fromthe teacher's desk, he only accepts one pupil at a time, other forced tostand and wait.

The walls of this room have a very different character from the rest ofthe building, made of a strange blue-black metallic substance.  This insideof the door is covered in the same metal, meant to absorb any extraneousmagic.  The purpose of this room is to provide the apprentices a place topractice where they aren't putting anyone's life at risk, save perhaps theirown.

The spiral stair ends here on a wide landing.  A narrower, wooden staircontinues upwards to an iron door marked '`bprivate`l'.  A thick, blackcurtain hangs over an archway to the north, and an open archway leads intothe magical supply shop to the west.

This small, plain room is solid black.  The walls and ceiling areebony-hued stone, while a thin padded mat, pitch black, covers the floor.The scent of incense fills the air, though none is visibly burning.  The humof magical energy seems to throb rhythmically, like the flow of blood inveins, encouraging meditation and mental relaxation.

The elders of the order create the items and familiars available at thisshop to keep their skills sharp.  The prices are generally far fromreasonable, the elders often getting overly attached to their creations.None of the inventory is visible, only a printed item and price list on thefar wall next to a simple stone counter.

From a raised platform on the side, the Guild Master surveys the entirepractice area with an experienced eye, quick to catch the slightest flaw inform.  His gaze is unreadable as he watches young recruits struggle tostrike the dummies effectively while maintaining a good defensive stance.

The massive roots of a large tree located somewhere above, randomlycriss-cross the earthen ceiling of this large, round chamber.  Soft, pillowymoss covers the ground here instead of the smooth, gray stones of the otherchambers.  A small hole in the ceiling allows sunlight to fill the dimchamber.

Lavishly decorated with plush carpeting and hard wood arches along theceiling, someone has spared no expense in furnishing the best here.  Thethick, polished table is clean, all notes from the last meeting carefullyremoved from the prying eyes of the staff and recruits.  The elders of theorder usually use the meeting room in the castle, using this room only as asecond choice.

This small chapel has been designed as a classroom for aspiring clerics.There is a small altar at the front, where the teacher stands to preach tothe young acolytes.  Several tile frescoes line the walls, depicting morallessons important for the master's pupils.  A heavy oaken door to the southleads to a small, secluded courtyard where acolytes learn how to defendthemselves from those that would lead them astray.

Two wide steps lead up to the altar, a semi-circle of black obsidian witha large obelisk at its center.  The obelisk has a silver triskelion set intothe stone, shining starkly bright against the black background.  The flooris 3 solid pieces of stone, the seams of the center on making a perfectsquare in front of the obelisk.  A small unmarked door is set into the wallto the east.

The room is quite comfortable, with plush velvet curtains and softcarpeting.  The bed looks welcoming and relaxing, drawing you towards it forsome much needed rest.  A painting of a battle taking place amidst a fiercestorm hangs on the wall behind the bed.

The office is surprisingly small and cramped, the shelves lined withscriptures.  Only one small window lets in natural light from outside, highup in the eastern wall.  The floor is carpeted with a thick rug woven withimages of flames, a homage to the fire aspect of the one god.

You are at the bottom of a cylindrical pit, at least twenty feet belowthe cathedral altar.  The floor is stained rust red, darker in some spots.Broken bones lie scattered on the ground, clearly human, some quite old,some still with flesh clinging to the surface.

A narrow dirt road, barely wide enough to let a wagon pass, leads offinto the woods to the west.  To the east, two towers stand on either side ofthe gates of Thesden.  You can hear the rumble of the crowds pouring out ofthe town and disturbing the peace of this quiet forest.  A short path to thenorth leads to a small clearing.

This small tunnel looks like a good place to take shelter from theelements.  It is short and comfortable, easily wide enough for you to movedown, just about the breadth of your shoulders.  The floor is dirt, firmlypacked, likely from some animal making its home here.

It is difficult to tell if this chamber was carved by human hands or byforce of nature.  Rounded stones make comfortable seats throughout the room,and a tiny waterfall pours out of the wall, sparkling in the faint light.  Ashort passage leads to the north and west.  The only other exit is backthrough the secret door to the east.
The walls of this small, comfortable chamber are earth and stone.  Theceiling is a fine mesh of roots, woven together by ages of growth.  A shortpassage leads back into the main hall to the south.

A semi-circle of comfortable chairs all face a small stage at the frontof this room.  A number of music stands are spread about the room, among thestudent's chairs.  A black board hangs behind the stage, lines for musicalnotation permanently marked across it.
This plain room is undecorated and uncarpeted, just a simple bed withwhite blankets.  A single window, framed in woolen brown curtains, looks outon the square below.

Smoke swirls around the lanterns in this small room, pouring from thepipes of the elders who meet in here to discuss plans.  The room is cozy, afew padded chairs spread about with small tables.  Drinks are brought fromthe Spider's Ring, mixed with other substances consumed in the back room.

You walk into a humble abode, ducking your head to avoid bashing itagainst the low ceiling.  This home boasts no windows, and would beunbearably hot in the summer if not for the thick stone walls' remarkableretention of cool air.  The home is sparsely furnished, providing its ownerwith the simplest of comforts.  Judging from the various imported sundries,you surmise that this house belongs to one who has travelled the easternseas, or at least belongs to someone who knows such intrepid adventurers.

The floor of this small home is covered with an intricately woven rugthat contrasts greatly with the unadorned walls.  This is a well kept home,evidenced by the dustless floor and the well arranged floral pots that lineThe vivid color of the flowers matches the designs of the rug.  It looks asif someone takes great care in upkeeping the asthetics of this place.

The ocean chruns on, sea-foam and shells, driving skelatal once-fish andthe glassy-crystal remains of a jellyfish broken by a storm.  The watersswirl on, salty and dark, grinding to sand the last stones of what once wasa mountain.  The cycle rolls on, a clump of greenish seaweed riding thefroth of a wave from the other side of the world.  A perpetual inventory ofthe sea, awash with debris, alive and dead, inevitable and silent.

Mostly bare and sparsely furnished, the most alluring embellishments ofthis humble home are the streaks of light coursing in through the thatchedstraw roof.  The illumination creates strange shapes of the shadows,elongating the corners of the room, and giving the house a complexity fargreater than its reality.  Hidden in the peaceful proximity of CathedralSquare, the family that lives here, most likely aspiring apprentices, enjoysan amiable existence.

The water is clear and lifeless here, swirling out as you enter to mixwith the polluted river above.  This ancient chamber is decorated with anumber of skeletons, a few rusted weapons, and an old ship's anchor.  Youcan only guess at what long dead pirate made this place, and what may liewithin.

An impressive stone arch rises far above your head, extending into ashort corridor which open onto the `g`kArena of Legends`l`l on the otherside.  The arch stones are massive granite blocks, each as tall as a man.Along the corridor, carved in the same dusty granite stone, are the statuesof ancient champions, preserved forever for their prowess in the arena.

This tiny shop has no shelves, just a plain desk on which is carefullypinned a number of elaborate ship plans.  Pinned along the walls are plansfor many ships from sloops to frigates, along with dramatic oil paintings ofthe ships braving rough seas or sailing into the setting sun.  MasterAsrac's work does not come cheap, but is famed for being able to hold up inseas too rough for any other ship.  A piece of vellum hangs as a`d sign`l on one ofthe walls.``

The time-worn wood of the docks creaks and sways slightly with eachfootstep.  The masts of ships stand out among a forest of ropes to the eastand west.  A few ships with sails raised pull out heading to the open ocean,slowly shrinking to white dots on the horizon.  The docks continue to thesouth.
The larger ships, frigates and merchantmen are docked here, further outinto the bay.  Sailors move about the decks, hanging from ropes and loadingcargo.  The docks continue to the south.
The larger ships, frigates and merchantmen are docked here, further outinto the bay.  Sailors move about the decks, hanging from ropes and loadingcargo.  The docks continue to the south and east.
The larger ships, frigates and merchantmen are docked here, further outinto the bay.  Sailors move about the decks, hanging from ropes and loadingcargo.  The docks continue to the south.

The docks end here, only the small rolling waves of the bay can be seento the south.  Large merchant frigates float in the water along the pier,rising and falling with the waves.  Ropes as thick as your leg hold theships in port, tied safely to the creaking docks.

This small section of dock is home to many of the ships of the thesdennavy.  The ships are carefully gaurded and are floating a good 20 feet fromthe pier.  A few other ships float among the navy ships, mainly smallpassenger or merchant sloops.

Rooms.RoomDescription: The small ship's draft is small, floating almost on the surface of thewater.  The deck shifts slightly with each passing wave, the single mastswaying with it.  The sail's bloom in the wind, driving the ship through thewater, slicing the waves, faster than any galleon or frigate.  A narrowladder leads down into the ship's hold.

This round-hulled ship is perhaps thirty feet long, with two masts, thelarger in the rear.  The sails rise high above the deck, casting shdows overthe wheel.  At full-speed, the ship cuts through the waves rather thanrolling upon them.  A ladder leads below deck here.

The barque is the largest of the round-hulled ships, with a deck nearlythirty paces long, with two main masts and three sails.  The passing wavesonly shift the deck slightly, the steady swaying making you slightly ill.  Awide step-ladder leads down below deck here.

The narrow stone staircase ends into this bleak hallway.  The walls andfloor are cold grey stone, each footsteps echo down its length off the steeldoors of the prison cells to the north and south.  No one enters this placewithout reason, and when you find yourself here, your future is dismal anddim.

This dark hallway is lined with heavy steel doors, each with a tinybarred window.  The air is still and musky, filled with the scents of sweatand mildew.  It is painfully cold, the heat dissapating into the hard stonewalls and the earth beyond.  A stairwell to the south leads out of thislonely hell.

The lonely cries and screams of the prisoners echo out from behind theheavy steel doors and reverberate in this narrow hall which runs from northto south.  No light reaches the hall, the cold and darkness making thisprison into a torture chamber as well.

Rooms.RoomDescription: These cells are reserved for the worst and most hated criminals, toosmall to live in for any length of time.  The ceiling is low, so low that itis impossible to stand, and the walls are too narrow to lie down.  Only atiny sliver of light reaches inside, making the darkness not quite entirelyblack, everything appears as blurred greys.  The heavy steel door iswindowless and imposing.  A small, dirty mirror hangs crookedly on one wall.

A tiny, filthy mirror shines alittle bit, an odd concession to vanity in this miserable little room.  Theheavy steel door is windowless and imposing.

Three short paces carry you across the length of this dismal cell.  Thewalls are grey and covered in stains, water marks from the steady leaks nearthe ceiling mixed with unidentifieble rust-red marks on the walls andfloors.  It is cold, the stone floors sapping the warmth from your body justas surely as the cell saps your hope.  Only a narrow shaft of light comesthrough the barred window, tracing a slow path across the floor, marking theendless hours of your lonely days.  A muck-encrusted mirror hangs forlornlyon one wall.

A steel door to the east seals you in the desolation of this dank cell,only a small window opens onto the hall, the darkness of which inspireslittle hope. The unkempt man in the stall smileswickedly as you approach, awaiting yet another sale.

Interlocking crests of every shade of imaginable green fill the air aboveyou as you stroll underneath the cool canopy of tangled ferns that archabove the tiled walkway here.  The pungent smell of flora and wild animalsassaults you for a brief moment, and is carried away on a quick breeze thenext instant.  Chirps and tweets echo throughout the small tunnel ofgreenery, filling the air with an odd sequential melody that seems somehowappropriate for this marvelous zoo.

As you walk through the shaded greenery,the cacophony of animal howls and chirps makes you wonder how peacefulthis spot would be if it weren't for the constant wails.

Thick squares of dusk-streaked limestone wobble slightly within theirtar encasement as you step across them and make your way along thepromenade.  A thin layer of clear glaze makes the light from artificialsources above you dissolve into a radiance that seems to emergeunhindered from the ground itself.  The spectacle of wild animals inevery direction almost makes you lose your footing as you continue alongon the unstable path.

Bluish-green leaves dangle from the branches of two polarized trees thattouch briefly in the air above you.  Winding stems from long-neckedflowers meet with thin twigs, exploding into various colors of flowerblossoms and fruits at their termination.  The ends of tiny vines andferns brush the top of your head as you wander underneath the greatcanopy, making you look up occasionally for an unseen foe.

In the distance in every direction you can see tents and cagesfilled with howling creatures of all types.  The air around you seemsstagnant with the smell of captured wildlife and greenery, causing youto wrinkle your nose slightly as you amble about.

Rooms.RoomName: A humid trail around a murky pit
Rooms.RoomDescription: Soft peat outlines an even softer trail of dampened soil and gravel here,and dips off to merge with a moss-green pool of water and debris.  Oddshapes linger about under the pit water's surface, gliding silentlyback and forth while not revealing their entire form.  A yellowed eyeemerges from the filth as you watch the water's surface, and stares atyou briefly before sinking into the depths once more.

You now stand in the center of the animal exhibition sprawl.  The tiledwalkway extends in all directions, leading to tents in the distance, andanimal pens in almost every direction.  A cold gust of wind washes overyou as you pass through the middle of the display, reminding you of thediffering climactic conditions that need to be reproduced in order to keepsome of the animals here alive.  Swinging steel gates offer a quick `bexit`l`l toWelford Road from here should one wish to leave the zoo.

The slight glaze that covers the limestone bricks makes it easy to loseyour footing as you walk along the wobbly stone platform that houses themain area of the exhibition.  Striped tents can be seen off in the distance,and an assortment of pits and cages lie in every direction.  Near theiron gates on the horizon you can see a U-shaped canopy circling the area,and what seems to be a roost for birds and insects.

Grains of shining golden sand sparkle on the dust-caked slabs of rock thatsit overlooking the oval body of clear blue water.  Surrounding the poolis an assortment of red and yellow rocks, that act as barriers to theamphibious creatures that reside within it.  Within the crystal waters youcan see various lifeforms paddling about underneath, and diving intohidden coves under the surface.

A shelf made of pale yellow rock juts out over an elliptical pool ofbrilliant blue water, casting a triangular shadow over it.  Small fishand other creatures swim around in the exposed refracted light, whileothers hibernate solemnly underneath the rock.  Surrounding the poolare groups of fire-colored rocks, keeping the inhabitants of the areaenclosed within.

Dark brown soil bulges in deformed spherical domes, creating a miniaturehill range that makes travelling this path a bit more difficult than walkingon hardened ground.  Pools of gravel fill the ruts in the ground, an obviousattempt to stabilize the path by the owners of the exhibition.  Off in thedistance north, you can see the flaps of huge striped tents waving in thewind.

Gigantic striped monoliths of burlap and sackcloth tower above you,unbroken pillars of cloth only marred by the thin metal catches at thebase that mark the doorflaps of the tent.  You can hear the drone ofwailing animals and screaming people echoing out from the inside of theedifice.  Slabs of limestone form a promenade around you, and animalcages lie in almost every direction.

The huge striped tents that tower above you seem to sway slowly as a hardbreeze hits their flanks, giving the illusion of faint movement.  Steelrods jut out from the ground at every corner of the squarish tent, suspendingthe cloth structure high in the air above you.  Behind you, the sprawlof the limestone promenade spreads out.

Small, filthy creatures cruise by you and dive into the mudholesthat seem to fill the sticky ground, poking eyestalks out of the murkto stare up at you.  Above you, a patch of damp ground encircles thedirty pool, offering a way out should you choose to leave.

The slanted canvas walls of the tent house a clean wooden platform filledwith barrels and containers of all sizes, all containing food of differingtypes. Small pits in the ground house newborn creatures until they are readyto be released either into the wild or into captivity in the zooestablishment.  Squeals from the small creatures erupt in faint burstsas you pass, and tiny claws reach up out of the pits to grab at yourankles, searching for food.

A dusty yellow rock shelf to the north overlooks this clear blue bodyof water.  Watergulls soar overhead and perch on the muddy red rocksthat frame the pool, scanning the water for fish and other edibles.North of here lies the rock shelf, and beyond that, the limestonepromenade.

Outside of the cage, you can see thesprawl of the promenade, with tents off in the distance.

Outside, huge colored tentstower off into the sky, making your entrapment here seem even worse.

The walls of the room are covered by shelves filled withbooks and chests containing powerful knowledge and artifacts.  The room is socluttered that one could hardly move through it, and the air is filled withthe penetrating stench of evil, but curiosity and the unquenchable thirst forpower draws you further in.

This room is filled with all sorts of trinkets gathered by Morian during his manyyears of life.  The shelves line the room from wall to wall, each with a differentset of items, all somehow alike but unique at the same time.  Among the items onthe shelves are "Nudie Pictures of Cailet and Murk" and the "Plunger of Depravity".A glass case lies in the middle of the room, storing the most powerful of items.

You have to duck your head as you pass beneath the roots from a treeabove, which hang down through the ceiling.  When you stand up again, youfind yourself in a small shop beneath the Ranger guild.  An aged syvin plieshis wares here, retired from a long career tracking in the woods and wildlands of the world.

`aSmall `ks`ou`kn`ob`ke`oa`km`os `amake their way through intricate slitsin the old carved storeroom.  Old `dbarrels `aof rotten food litter thefloor.  `aWhile once a place for guards to rest during breaks and enjoy apipe of tobacco while eating and sharing a story, it is now a gloomy anddark place, long gone are the sounds of laughter, the smell of tobacco smokerising into the air, `aand the smells of roast mutton being slowly cookedover a huge pit of flames.  Among the barrels are also small chests, theoutfit of the guard which once stayed in the tower.  `aA decrepit rangereyes you from the corner of the room, a one handed haggard looking thing,before finally nodding and tossing you the keys before laying back down inhis solitary prison.  ``

Magical and ancient energies engulf the atmosphere in an electric`i fire`l.  Awizened and ancient artificer sits behind his desk mumbling ancient incantations tothe`o Elder King`l.  Ancient texts line the walls in the form of`a books,`h scrolls,and`k parchments`l.  Behind his desk, the symbol`n *`g*`n*`l marks this shop as belongingto the ancient order of the`o Elder King`l.``
`mTHIS ROOM NEEDS A DESCRIPTION ASAP!``

Powerful runes of transportation has been inscribed into the walls ofthis room.  The room is empty, but an arcane circle is engraved into themarble floor, every line of runes seem to lead to this magic focal point.

Powerful runes of transportation has been inscribed into the walls ofthis room.  The room is empty, but an arcane circle is engraved into themarble floor, every line of runes seem to lead to this magic focal point.
`mtell iverath if you want a desc for this(write the desc first)``
`qThis room should have a description, but it doesn't because someone was too lazy togive the people in charge a room description.  Maybe it should have one.``

The air is muggy and misty;  dampness covers the ground.  A man stands in the middleholding lots of treasure of untold.  The treasure he holds looks to be like a largepile of booty.  He awaits you to buy some of his booty, and to move on happy.

`hThe rumored broom closet of the crystal castle!  You always wanted tovisit here and now your wish has come true!  Over there is the legendarysinging bucket of herrings, and over there the fabled floor that is aceiling!  There is even a guy selling souvenirs here.``

Rooms.RoomName: `fAt the Bottom of the Golden Stairs``
Rooms.RoomDescription: `hYou are still in the hall of this great castle, and you just know thatup these stairs there will be riches beyond your over-active imagination.Just upstairs you will find the cure to every illness, the answer to anyquestion and matching shoes.  Just a few dozen steps away...  ``

Rooms.RoomName: A dusty back room above the town hall

Rooms.EnterMsg: `g$n enters the shop, gaping at the polished weapons displayed.``
Rooms.ExitMsg: `gThe sound of footsteps echoes through the hallway as $n leaves.``

Rooms.RoomDescription: `gThe ocean roars above you and all around.  You seem to be in a bubbleof air floating adrift in the vast icey blue water that is the ocean.Tropical fish and eels are visible through the opacity of the bubble you arein.  There are no signs of the bubble walls, its as if you are standing atthe bottom of the ocean, dry to the bone.  Although the ground looks likethe floor of the ocean, boasting coral, rocks, and algei, it feels soft likeshag carpeting.``

Rooms.RoomName: The Second Floor of the Pub
Rooms.RoomDescription: `lOnce an often visited "love nest" run by Gillian herself, this skeletonof a room, is nothing like it used to be.  No soft beds or satin sheets.  Nowoven carpets or silken tapestries.  All that is left is a roof and twowalls, one to the east and the other to the west.  The glass in the windowframes was destroyed long ago by either children with rocks, or heavy blindbirds.  Through the chimney of`b the Pub`l you hear drunken discussions ofthe partons.  Now and then you hear Gillian's laugh, which can only bedescribed as a kind of high-pitched neighing.  ``

Rooms.RoomName: Walking a Beam Far Above an Alley
Rooms.RoomDescription: Below you, in the alley, beggars lie in the filth, talking to eachotheras if their situation in life isn't that bad after all.  The beam you standon seems sturdy enough, and in both ends it is secured with oiled chains.

Rooms.EnterMsg: Holding $s breath, $n leaves the meat locker.
Rooms.ExitMsg: Holding $m breath, $n leaves the meat locker.
Rooms.RoomDescription: Cows, sheep and pigs make a terrible noise as they stare panicky at thevery dead chunks of meat that was once their relatives.  They are kept incheck by iron cages, leaving them no choice except to eat, poo, and wait fortheir time to get slaughtered.  You notice a small hole up on the northwall, it must be for ventilation, it looks like a person could fit throughthat hole, but how would anyone get up there?

Rooms.RoomName: Walking a Rope High Above Cumberland Avenue
Rooms.RoomDescription: Balancing on a tight rope would be dangerous, if it wasnt for the factthat you and your kind have been balancing on rooftops all your life.People, mostly young people, flock to the pub below, probably planning todrink ale instead of eating real food.

Rooms.RoomName: Sneaking Across the Rooftops of Thesden
Rooms.RoomDescription: You are walking across a flat roof, to the east is a locked window, andyou know what locked means.  Something valuable is on the other side, be itgold or a merchant's daughter.  But of course, you are too honorable to eventhink of breaking into someone else's home, right?

A sea of roofs surrounds you, pidgeons occupying every ledge, clotheslineand chimney.  The otherwise loud noise of Thesden is now only a buzz.  Uphere, you actually take notice of the sky.  The roofs supply the perfectsanctuary for people who might not always agree with the lawmen patrollingthe streets below.
As you look to the northwest you see the well known marble fountain ofDevon Square.  You can barely make out the people standing around it,perhaps the binoculars placed here would help?

Rooms.EnterMsg: A panel opens and $n crawl out on the ledge.
Rooms.ExitMsg: $n disappears behind a panel.
Rooms.RoomDescription: Keeping the balance is child's play in your line of profession, andthough the drop to the street below seems awfully long, you are not afraid.Sneaking across the ledges, that are commonly found on the buildings inThesden, and in through the second story window is a well known way ofbreaking an entry.  Far below, people are moving about, handling theirbusiness on the street of Seahan Way.

Rooms.MaxMsg: You see the boots of someone sticking out from under the half-closed panel, there is not enough ROOM to crawl in there.
Rooms.RoomDescription: `aBeing a rogue, crawling in secret spaces, under floors, paddlingthrough sewers, is usual day to day work.  However that does not make it onebit more comfortable when splinters from the rough boards digs into yourback, knees and hands.  ``

Rooms.RoomName: On the Roof of the Bakery
Rooms.RoomDescription: The smell of freshly baked bread surrounds you.  For this scent alone youwould probably hang around here more often.  If only it wasn't for that shedand its stench of blood.  ``

Rooms.RoomName: On the Roof Across from the Apothecary
Rooms.RoomDescription: Stealthily peeking over the edge of the roof, you see the Leech and RootApotechary.  The usual patrons are there, recieving Zannah's expert healing.Little do they know that you can see them, and that you are wel prepared foran ambush as soon as they step out on Seahan Way, just below you.  Out ofthe sheer boredom of waiting, you test your knife's sharpness on a nearbypidgeon.

This shack looks rather normal, for a butcher's shop.  Too bad that it'sNOT a butcher's shop but a sawbones shack.  Grim saws and knives hang on thewalls, and for some reason you don't spot any bandages...  The steelexamination table at the back wall is dyed black from blood, and the closestwall and floor are splattered with, what you think must be, blood too.  Asyou look closer, you see marks on the wall next to the examination table,claw marks.  It doesn't appear that Dr.  Giggles supply the luxury ofpainkillers or sedatives with his operations.
This plank is just wide enough for your foot, good thing dexterity isyour main stat.

Rooms.EnterMsg: Careful not to fall through the trapdoor, $n stalks into the room.
Rooms.RoomName: By the Trapdoor Above the Candle Shop
Rooms.RoomDescription: Since so many seem to need a light, after loosing their equipment in someaccident.  People with grave injuries wobble to Simon's Candle Shop to getone.  Of course, this is where the less powerful assassins and thieves maketheir kills.  A well placed stiletto has been the end of many adventurers inthis shop.

This alley doesn't look that bad, well, except for that guy over there,the guy with the knife.  And that dog growling at you, guarding his heap oftrash.  And what did you just step in?  What IS that smell?  You hear ascream and a thump nearby and wisely decide to move on.
`aThis storage room isn't exactly worn from use, but has somehow aquiredthe nasty smell of a tavern back room anyways.  ``

Rooms.ExitMsg: A shadow slinks by.
Rooms.RoomDescription: So THIS is where all of the city's bums are hiding!  One of them nods atyou and points toward the open grate in the middle of the alley.

Rooms.EnterMsg: Almost tripping over the various objects lying around, $n stumbles into the shop.
Rooms.RoomDescription: `aShelves, glass cases, the floor, the counter, even on Spink himself,you find colorful items of all kinds.  Like some kind of human-sized magpie,Spink seems to have picked up every shiny object he ever laid his greedyeyes on, just to put it on display in this shop.  ``

`aRunning across the wooden plank in the middle of the damp passage, youpass`k torches`a and the occasional skeleton (nothing unusual in this partof town).  Rats scurry out of your way as you continue towards your desination.``
`aSo this is where the passage was leading, to some old stairs.  No doubtgiving you access to another shady part of town.  You catch a whiff ofliquor from the door at the top of the stairs.  ``

Rooms.RoomName: Back Room of the Merchant's Guild

Rooms.TpMsg: Oh yeah, really clever about finding the torch, unless someone told you the secret, then you're just a copycat. Anyways, here is 10,000 experience points.
Rooms.ExitMsg: passage
Rooms.RoomDescription: `aA small chamber, room for little else than for two thieves splittingtheir loot.  A torch lights up the chamber, the smoke seaps into a smallhole in the wall.  Probably ending up seeping out somewhere on WestCumberland Avenue.  ``

You look down on Pine Street, stretching from The Cathedral to the RavenSquare.  Priests, workers and merchants are doing their chores, hurryingabout.  The guards are patrolling their designated routes, looking forthieves and troublemakers, however, none of them are looking up at the roofsof Thesden...

This looks like a rather normal office, even if its richly decorated withwooden panels, thick carpets and golden linings on the furniture.  Thoughknowing the nature of Pook, you suspect that there is more than one secretcompartment in this room.  The windows to the east and north provide light.

Rooms.RoomName: On the top of the Stairs

Rooms.TpMsg: You get 500 experience points for breaking into this pink bedroom, on this MUD we encourage thievery.
Rooms.EnterMsg: Someone sneaks in through the window, probably ANOTHER burglar.
Rooms.RoomDescription: Even though this room is rather..  Well..  Pink, you notice that it mustbelong to a wealthy person.  Pink curtains flap in the wind as you break in,you notice that there is someone on the bed (clad in pink, you guessed it).

Rooms.RoomName: Entrance to the Mansion of Pook
Rooms.RoomDescription: You stare in amazement at the entrance hall before you, last you saw thiswhite marble was when you visited the King's Castle.  Tapestries cover thewalls, and lush, dark green carpets the floor.  Doors lead in alldirections, probably to equally grand rooms.  Pook, the owner of thismansion must be very wealthy, of course it would be hard not to be wealthy,being King Athanmere's bastard son and all.  A grand staircase leads up tothe second floor where you can see a painting, framed in gold, portrayingPook throwing gold to the masses.  Servants scurry out of your way, headsbowed, as you enter the hall.

This passageway leads east and west.  Throught the darkness.  You can seevery little in either direction.  A cold draft keeps the hairs on your neckon end and makes it very difficult to relax.  There is something very evilabout this place.

Rooms.MaxMsg: `lYou're not cool enough, sorry.``
Rooms.TpMsg: `kCool, you found a new place, 500xp for you!``
Rooms.EnterMsg: `o$n is here! Yay! Woo! Wee!``
Rooms.ExitMsg: $n jumps off the cloud!

Rooms.RoomDescription: `bJust a moment, you are being digested.``

Rooms.EnterMsg: $n wanders into the map room looking for directions.
Rooms.ExitMsg: Satisfied with the directions, $n leaves the basement.
Rooms.RoomDescription: The basement under Thesden's town hall was opened to the public so thatpeople new to the world of Exodus could have a reference to find their wayaround.  Maps are pinned all over the walls, newer ones covering up part ofolder ones.  There are also a number of tables and desks here overflowingwith maps to all kinds of useful places.  A wooden staircase leads back upto the town hall above.
`hEach step is higher than the one before it, forcing you to hop up thestairs like a giant bunny with too-colorful clothes (although no fur, gottaget fur).  ``
This muddy beach seems to be used as a junkyard, litter is all around.West of here is the murky waters of the river, and east of here is OldCobble Road.
`aThis cell was designed specifically to house the most notorious Reavers of the realm.``

A rotted wooden gate and heavy iron portcullis block the way to thenorth.  The portcullis appears to be nearly rusted through, and the wormsvisibly chewing through the gate don't inspire confidence in this town'sdefenses.  A cobbled muddy road leads to the south into town, and a sturdydoor to the east leads into the guard tower which rises to the city wall.

This weathered cobble-stone street is covered in mud and dirt.Grim-faced peasents make their way along the sides, watching their feet.  Anassortment of minature clan symbols decorate the wide doorway of the large,wooden building to the east of here.

This weathered cobble-stone street is covered in mud and dirt.  A murkygreen-brown river runs along the side of the road to the west.  The stenchcarried on the breeze from the river makes you realize where this towndisposes of their sewage.

This weathered cobble-stone street is covered in dirt and mud.  A foulsmelling murky river runs parrelel to the road just to the west.  To thesouth the road opens into a wide square.  To the east, a three storyofficial-looking building rises above the squalor of the surroundingbuildings.  A small dignified sign marks it as the court building ofThesden.

This small square spreads out to the south and east.  Wide slate stonescover the ground mixed with dirt and mud.  A crowd is gathered to the southin front of the grim walls of the prison.  A cobbled road leads to thenorth, and to the west a wooden bridge spans the river.

Wide slate stones cover the ground of this small square.  Few people canbe found here, those that are seem to be in a hurry to get somewhere else orare gathered in a crowd in the southwest corner.  Larger crowds can be seento the east moving along Cumberland Avenue.  To the north stands the Thesdencourthouse, rising three stories above the square.  Its windows face outonto the gallows and the prison beyond to the south.

This square is considerably more bland than the other squares of the cityno fountains, statues or monuments...  Just a grim gallows to the west.  Thewide paving stones are, however, carefully swept and the whole place hasquite an official feel to it.  Two sturdy wooden doors mark the entrance tothe town militia headquarters to the south.

A crowd has gathered in this corner of the square before the grey wallsof the prison.  This is the site of public executions of those caughtstealing, killing, or in the wrong place at the wrong time.  The head of arecent victim lies impaled on a spike just outside the prison gate to thesouth.

This wooden bridge may have once been white, but the years have treatedit badly, fading it to its current grey and brown.  The beams creak underthe strain of feet, though the others on the bridge don't seem much afraidof it falling.  A foul-smelling, murky green river runs beneath the bridge.

You are on the dark, swirling waters of the Severn River.  You could diveunder the murky waters, though the vague stench of sewage makes you thinkyou might regret it.  A rotting wooden bridge casts a shadow on you, ithangs low and you could easily pull yourself out of the water by climbingonto it.
You are on the dark, swirling waters of the Severn River.  You could diveunder the murky waters, though the vague stench of sewage makes you thinkyou might regret it.  The rivers runs north to south.

You are on the dark, swirling waters of the Severn River.  You could diveunder the murky waters, though the vague stench of sewage makes you thinkyou might regret it.  The river runs north to south, you can climb up onto ashort muddy beach to the east.

You are on the dark, swirling waters of the Severn River.  You could diveunder the murky waters, though the vague stench of sewage makes you thinkyou might regret it.  The river curves here, running from the west to thesouth towards the ocean.

You are on the dark, swirling waters of the Severn River.  You could diveunder the murky waters, though the vague stench of sewage makes you thinkyou might regret it.  The river curves here from the north to the east.

You are above the dark, swirling waters of the Severn River.  You coulddive under the murky waters, though the vague stench of sewage makes outhink you might regret it.  The river curves here, running from the west tothe south.

You are above the dark, swirling waters of the Severn River.  You coulddive under the murky waters, though the vague stench of sewage makes youthink you might regret it.  The river runs from west to east.

The prison guard room is quite plain, giving a clear panoptical view ofthe cells on this floor.  A narrow stone stairwell leads down to the lowercells.  A door leads to the guard head quarters to the east, and larger irondoors open into Gallows Square to the north.

This small cell has little room to move around, you can get across it injust 2 steps.  The door is made of iron, with only a small barred window.Another small window to the west looks out on the murky waters of the SevernRiver.

This cell looks like it is meant to hold a number of prisoners, thoughcertainly not comfortably.  A heavy iron door blocks the way to the guardroom to the north, with only a small barred window letting light into theroom.  There are no other windows, each wall is solid stone.

This is the headquarters of the town guard.  The guard is made up mostlyof locals, trained briefly before they are put on the job.  The guard takescare of all the minor crimes and day to day keeping of the peace, the majorcrimes are left to the king's knights who are not nearly as merciful as theguardsmen.

Rooms.EnterMsg: `g$n slips quietly into the shop.``
Rooms.ExitMsg: `dYou hear just a quiet rustle as $n steps out.``
Rooms.RoomDescription: A wide variety of instruments, mostly stringed, hang from the walls andsit in the racks of this shop.  Some small benches are spread about theshop, giving you a place to sit while you try out some of the goods.  Mostof them bear a silvery white feather emblazoned on the neck, the sign of thelutier Evyln Swan.

Rooms.EnterMsg: `cThe crowd shuffles as `j$n `csqueezes in.``
Rooms.ExitMsg: `bThere's a little more room as `i$n `bleaves.``
Rooms.RoomDescription: Fresh pies, bread, cakes, and pastries rest on the shelves around thisshop.  People crowd into the shop tightly, waiting for a turn to order.  Thepress of bodies combined with the heat of the large oven make this smallshop swelteringly hot.

You are swimming in the foul waters of the Severn River.  The waters aremurky and dark, you find it quite difficult to see anything.  The swirlingwaters carry some small fish, and much else not nearly so harmless.

The main avenue of Thesden is always crowded; heavy merchant wagonstravel along the center in time-worn ruts in the road, travelers andpeasants move along the sides entering shops or begging for a coin.  Anumber of strange sounds are coming from the building to the north, outsidehangs a wooden sign which reads `m'The Gem Game'`l.  Another sign,painted in dripping crimson paint above the pub to the south reads`b'Hangman's Tavern'`l reminding you that gallows square is located just tothe west.

As you enter this shop, an interesting mixture of scents, somethingbetween eu du sewage and skunk, but not as pleasant as either, greets yournose.  You hear growls, hoots, and whistles coming from the back room.Loris, a famous traveler in his youth, has settled here to run this shop.
Mmm.  Smells bad in here.  You shouldn't be here.  Obviously, nobody elsecomes here judging from the way the animals view you.

Buildings made of dark, sturdy woods line the sides of this wide street,some as tall as four stories.  The lack of waste being thrown from highwindows attests to the fact that Thesden's limited sewer system does reachthese buildings at least.  A steady stream of people flows from Devon'sSquare to the east, heading to the west side on Cumberland.

The largest square in the city is filled with people of everytrying to earn a coin.  Majestic stone monuments and fountains rest in thecenter and corners, memorials to previous kings or for wars won.  The thickgolden paving stones turn to slate to the west in the direction ofCumberland Avenue.

The faint sounds of strings being plucked can be heard as you reach thiscorner of the square.  People shuffle past on both sides, heading to storesor on their way home.  A beautiful building, intricate vines carved into thewood around the door and windows, stands to the north with an understatedsign which reads `d'Wolsey Furnishings'`l.  The sound of instruments beinginexpertly played comes from `d'Swan's Feather Music'`l to the west.

The great square rumbles with the noise of the crowd, peddlers shoutingprices, water falling in fountains, wagons rolling along hard granite.  Adramatic fountain glints in the sun to the south, and along the square inother directions are shops of every description.  Seahan Way, lined withdark sloped-roof houses, leads off to the north.

`lThe smell of fresh bread fills this corner of the square, coming from the`a'`dOld Stoneoven Bakery`a'`l to the north.  A number of people are waiting inline outside the bakery for their turn at the counter.  A less popular butfar more expensive store,`a '`dThe Crystal Slipper Jeweler`a'`l lies just to theeast.``

The square sprawled out before you is filled with people of everydescription, from peasant farmer to rich merchant.  A massive bronzefountain glitters in the center to the west.  Around the outside of thecenter are shops for almost every need.  The flat slate stones of CumberlandAvenue lead off to the east.

The crowds thin slightly in this corner of the square, making way for thewagons which are gathered in front of the white building to the south.  Asmall sign outside names it 'The Satin Purse Merchant's Guild', a groupwhich organizes local merchants.  An exotic aroma comes from 'ThesdenImported Spices and Teas' to the east.

The great square rumbles with the sounds of the crowd, peddlers shoutingprices, wagons rolling on hard granite, water falling on the brass statuesof the fountain to the north.  Upscale shops line the sides, and to the westthe stone walls of the Town Hall can be seen.  Huge decadent homes standalong Seahan Way to the south.

A steady stream of people flow in and out of the wide doors of the'Thesden Town Hall' to the south.  The building is imposing and madeentirely of hard stone, it rises three stories, casting a deep shadow overthis section of the square.  A smaller wooden building to the west has abeautiful sign, worked in pure silver, which reads 'Ith's Silver andGoldsmithing'.

Rooms.TpMsg: This is Devon Square Center.  This is the center of activity in the city of Thesden.
Rooms.EnterMsg: $n strolls into the square.
Rooms.ExitMsg: $n melts off into the crowds of the square to the $T.
Rooms.RoomDescription: The fountain dominates the center of the square, surrounded by severalstone benches mixed among the few old elm trees that have survived.  Thewater from the fountain swirls into a pool, in which several large orangefish swim, searching hungrily for food.  Within the stonework of the square,an unlabelled map is set between two paving stones, slightly north of thefountain proper, and well-worn by numerous feet.

Dark, sloped-roof buildings line the sides of this quiet street.  A brasslantern hangs from a black pole, creating a flickering sphere of light inthe night.  During the day, shadows cast from tall buildings don't leave itmuch brighter.  Crowds of people fill Devon Square to the south.

The curtains are all closed in the buildings of this quiet street, theresidents of this district being notoriously secretive.  The sound of catsscreeching and fighting comes from a nearby alley, and only adds to thecreepiness.  A dark stone building with the attractive name `a'The Leech andRoot Apothecary'`l sits nestled between two taller building to the west.Seaham meets Raven Square to the north, and stretches towards the center oftown to the south.

`aThis square is paved in polished black slate, so dark it absorbs thelight from the air itself.  It is otherwise plain, none of the elaboratefountains or statues of the other squares.  A building stands imposingly tothe west, solid and without seams as if carved from a single piece of stone.Two hunched and twisted gargoyles loom over the narrow iron door.  A warmlight shines from the inside of a small, less chilling, structure to thenorth, `d'The Crow's Wing Inn'`a``.  `e`aSeahan Way leads off to the south, andPine street to the east.

This quiet side-street provides a substantially less dreary atmospherethan the dark stones of Raven Square to the west.  A narrow bed of paleflowers lies on each side of the street, carefully trimmed and watered.  Fewof the locals walk about here, however, and most head east towards theCathedral.

The quaint, orderly flowerbeds continue, giving a small note of color toan otherwise dreary street.  Large letters, crafted in wrought iron, runalong the top of a building to the south, reading `d'Goldmund's Antiques'`l.A tall, narrow building to the north has a plain wooden sign which reads,`d'Narcissus' Book Shop'`l.

This quiet side-street is well tended by the locals, quite a bit cleanerthan many of the others, and lined with neat flower beds.  Only a few peoplestroll by, and most seem fairly unhurried.  A sign above a shop to the southreads `d'Pine Street Tanner'`l.

A few grim town residents move along this quiet side-street.  Paleflowers crowd around the trunks of some small, pruned trees in beds alongthe sides, reaching for the few rays of light that make it past thesloped-roof homes and through the wide leaves.

Well pruned small trees and tidy flower beds line this quaint, narrowstreet.  The steeple of an imposing cathedral towers over the otherbuildings to the east, and Pine continues to the west.  `d'The CathedralGlassworks'`l is to the north, in a small shop with beautiful yellow and redstained glass windows.

The small square is paved with perfectly swept hexagonal grey and whitestones.  The white stones are arranged into three curving lines radiatingfrom the center, creating a huge triskelion, holy symbol of the Church.  Thegrand metal doors to the cathedral itself lie just to the east.  Thebuilding is imposing, dark stone surrounding richly colored stained glass,depicting the martyrs of the church dying by fire, water and steel.

A smattering of people walk along this quiet street.  The facades of theplain homes along the sides are lit by flickering bright lanterns at night,making you feel quite safe.  The road opens into Cathedral square to thenorth, and continues to the south.

Only a few people stroll along this quiet street, some merchants,citizens and a smattering of clergy from the cathedral.  A glittering brassand silver lantern hangs outside a shop to the west, a sign made of yellowwax that reads `k'Simon's Candle and Lantern'`l.
Plain wooden houses line this well lit street.  Not far off to the eastthe walls of Thesden can be seen, beyond which lay leagues of farmland.  Theroad continues, curving slightly, to the north.

Weary draft horses pulling crop-laden carts, farmers carrying heavy sacksof vegetables, and Thesden locals looking to buy the night's dinner all meetin this square.  To the east, a window reveals a number of animal carcassesinside `d'Estbury Meats and Poultry'`l.  The square spreads out to the westand south, and to the north lies Welford Road.

Wagons, carts, and men carrying heavy sacks flow in from the town gateto the east into this square which spreads out to the west and north.  Dirtand muck cake the ground, covered partially in hay to keep your feetsomewhat dry.  Welford road runs off to the south of here.

Two impressive stone towers loom over the gate, giving a wide visibilityto the guards who no doubt watch the lands to the east carefully.  Most ofthe crowds pouring in and out through the gate seem to be farmers coming tosell their crops in town, though a few more distant travelers are scatteredamongst them.

Dirt and muck cake your boots as you walk, winding past farmers and cartsfull of crops from the farms east of Thesden.  The scent of flower pollenwafts from a small shop to the west, `c'The Black Orchid Flowershop'`l.

Thick layers of dirt, gravel, and mud cover the surface of this squarewhich spreads out to the south and east.  The vague scent of manure fillsthe air, combining with other earthy scents and a faint trace of flowers.  Asign, drawn in an unsteady hand, which reads `c'Fresh Produce'`l, hangsoutside a rickety wooden stand to the north.  Cumberland Avenue leads off tothe west towards the center of town.

Most of the homes along this brick road are owned by farmers who earnedenough and preferred living within the city walls to their ancestral homes.The residents move about dressed in garish copies of the clothes of thenobility.  You guess there must be an interesting story about a sign to thewest, which reads: `d'The Dreadful Buzzard Tavern'`l.  Underneath hangs acarving of a vulture holding a long golden chain in its mouth.  East fromhere, you can see a large wooden sign proclaiming `c"Thesden AnimalExhibition Gardens"``.
The dust and muck from the Farmer's Square to the north thins to thesouth along the road, until finally the reddish paving stones become visibleonce again.

The slate stones clatter with footsteps, hooves and wagon wheels.  Thestreet looks worn by the years, and though nothing is obviously broken, thefaded paint and cracked stones tell the story of many harsh winters.  Thestreet continues to the east, and opens into the hurried mobs of DevonSquare to the west.  A wooden sign with the picture of a tankard on it hangsover the northern doorway.

A steady flow of people walk along Thesden's main avenue, heading towardshomes or shops.  Puddles gather in the cracked pacing stone, ripples rollingthrough them with each bootfall.  A clash of metal on metal comes from ashop to the south, a sign over the door reads `d'Wayland Blacksmith'`l.  ``

This wide street opens onto the mayhem of the farmer's markets to theeast, and continues west into the center of town.  Carefully tendedsloped-roof homes and shops stand along the sides, pleasant but not quitewelcoming.  A sign over a door to the north reads `d'Thesden WildernessSupply'`l, a painting above depicts a mountain rising out of a dense forest.

Burly, wealthy looking young men move along the road here, mostly headingsouth towards Grisedale square, but some entering `d'Mincer Ray'sWeaponry'`l to the west.  Not far the east, the stone walls of Thesden canbe seen, dividing the city from the farms beyond.

The square is usually filled with the squires and servants of the knightswho train and practice in the impressive stone structure to the east.  A fewrust-red stains on the grey marble of the square attest to the frequentfights among the young nobles, and their often unhappy ends.  A clear signwhich reads `d'The Whetstone Inn'`l hangs outside a large wooden house tothe south.  Welford Road leads to the north, and Langhan Street to the westof the square.

Students and young nobles walk along this street, coming from theKnight's Order in Grisedale square to the east, or from the Music Collegenot far to the west.  A shield with the yellow stripes is nailed above thedoor to the `d'Convent Armory'`l to the north.

Impressive, decadent homes line this road.  Most have the coat of arms ofone minor noble family or another, all too low ranking to live within thegates of the castle.  The high grey walls of Dunluce Castle can be seen notfar to the south, rising above the roofs of the houses.

Impressive, decadent homes line this road, most bearing the coat of armsof one of the minor noble families who are too low ranking to live withinthe castle gates.  The walls to Castle Dunluce itself can be seen loomingover the roofs of the houses to the south.

The wealthy section of Thesden continues along this neatly swept street.You are easily within a stone's throw of the massive walls of Castle Dunluceto the south.  A thin trail of smoke rises from the chimney of `d'PerthshireCeramics'`l to the north.

The sound of strings being played in a minor key wafts out of a spotlesswhite building with red trim to the south.  A sign outside reads `d'ThesdenCollege of Music'`l.  An avocation of the idle rich, only those born ofnoble blood and occasionally, an extremely talented commoner on scholarship,may study here.  Langhan Way opens into the magnificent Dorset Square to thewest, where its path of marble shimmers in the light.  Langhan Way continuesto the east, where houses and shops of grandeur can be found.

A majestic square spreads out from where you stand to the south and thewest, paved in marble with silvery inlays.  This square is where theThesdian nobles can be found, gossiping about the latest imports of silkenfrocks or the travesty of the drop in the price of Firensian spices.  SeahanWay leads off from here to the north towards Devon Square.  The faint soundof music can be heard floating this way from the east, down Langhan Street.

Lavishly dressed nobles stare down their noses at you as you walk acrossthe shimmering marble stones of the square, your footsteps echoing noisily,whereas their velvet slippered feet glide soundless across the surface.  Thedecadence of their lavish lifestyle is evident in the luxurious fabrics oftheir vestiments and the bold colors of their dress.  Through an iron gateto the west, you can see the greens of Ashton Gardens, beautifullylandscaped and dominated by an ancient, massive oak tree.

No beggars, peddlers, or for that matter anyone in less than the finestdress, can be found in this square.  The seals of Thesden's noble familiesare inlaid into the marble stone of the square in the finest silver.  Somuch wealth so close, but so impossible to reach.

No beggars can be found in this domain of the aristocracy, who keep thestreets near their houses clear of anything they don't want to see.  Thesquare meets two of Thesden's main street to the north, and to the south thegreat gates of Castle Dunluce stand, heavily guarded.

The gates to the Castle are made of thick wood, reinforced with puresteel.  In front of the gates is an iron portcullis, blackened with age.Rising above the grey walls of the castle rise ominously, crowned withrounded towers and barely visible gargoyles.

The homes are noticibly larger on the southern end of Seahan Way,dwarfing the merchant homes to the north.  To the south, the road opens intoDorset Square, home to many of the lesser nobles and locations of the gatesto the Castle.

A wide arch leads off this quiet street to the west into a stone buildingwith a domed roof.  `d'Thesden Savings Bank'`l is written along the top ofthe arch.  The street leads to Devon Square not far to the north, and DorsetSquare off to the south.

The shouts of the peddlers in Devon Square to the north echo off thelarge wooden homes of this street.  The mayhem of the square does not reachhere otherwise, and only a few citizens move along towards the gate toCastle Dunluce, visible far off to the south.  A tall granite archway leadsinto the arena to the east.  Cheers of the crowds within the massive,imposing building pour over the walls in a low rumble.

A thick layer of dirt and gravel cover the shattered paving stones of thestreet here.  The houses are remarkably smaller than those on the east sideof town, though they also seem much more populous.  The sound of childrenplaying and screaming mixes with the din of a hundred conversations on thestreet, filling the air with noise.  A worn wooden bridge crosses a murkyriver to the east, and the road continues to the west.

Wagon tracks make two parallel ruts through the dirt and crushed stone ofthis street.  Peasants and beggers mix with merchants headed to the docks orback to the wealthy districts on the east side.  The street opens into asmall square to the west and leads towards east Thesden to the east.
